OncoScore is distributed as a R Bioconductor package (https://bioconductor.org/packages/release/bioc/html/OncoScore.html ) in order to allow full  customization of the algorithm and easy integration in existing NGS pipelines, and as a web tool for  easy access by researchers with limited or no experience in bioinformatics (http://www.galseq.com/oncoscore.html ).

Comparative analysis  The results obtained by OncoScore were then compared with those of Gene Ranker  (http://cbio.mskcc.org/tcga-generanker/ )  2, a web tool extensively used to estimate the oncogenicity of  putative cancer genes.

Gene Ranker assigns a cancer score to each gene according to a complex set  of fixed properties (details can be found at: http://cbio.mskcc.org/tcga-generanker/sources.jsp ), where  the score associated with each gene is based on the confidence of the data used to generate the  prediction, therefore, from a functional point of view OncoScore and Gene Ranker are very similar.
To perform PubMed queries we took advantage of the public  API to the NCBI Entrez system: the NCBI E-utilities (http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK25500/).

9   Methods   Gene Datasets  The CGC dataset was collected from the Cancer Gene Census (CGC; version: November 2013;  http://www.sanger.ac.uk/scienc e/data/cancer-gene-census ) database, a set of genes causally  implicated in cancer.
PubMed accounts for more than 24 million citations of biomedical  literature from MEDLINE ( http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed ), from life science journals and from  online books.
If no match is found in any tables, terms are searched in All Fields and ANDed together (see  https://www.nlm.nih.gov/bsd/disted/pubmedtutorial/020_040.html ).
